Depending on the company, at this point you would be qualified for:
Even if it's not developing code, getting a job at a software company and
working in close proximity to software teams is a great way to learn
quickly, acquire mentorship, and gain practical experience.
The practical experience is valuable because it's very different than solo hobby
development and putting together your own apps. Mentorship is invaluable.
Your chances of getting a full-time job are much, much better if you have internships
or previous tech-related jobs on your resume. And because it's tech, you're paid
fairly well anyway. Some software interns earn $25/hr or more (do research).
Depending on the company, you might even be able to secure a full-time position.
But it's not as likely, because most employers will ask you algorithms and data
structures questions, which are in the next section.
